In [[astrophysics]] and [[physical cosmology]] the '''mass to light ratio''', normally designated with the Greek [[upsilon]] symbol <math>\Upsilon</math>,<ref>{{cite book |first1= Dimitri |last1= Mihalas |first2= Paul McRae |last2= Routly |date= 1968 |title= Galactic Astronomy |publisher= [[W. H. Freeman]] |pages= 257 |isbn= 9780716703266 }}</ref> is the quotient between the total [[mass]] of a [[spatial volume]] (typically on the scales of a [[galaxy]] or a [[galaxy cluster|cluster]]) and its [[luminosity]]. These ratios are often reported using the value calculated for the [[Sun]] as a baseline ratio which is a constant <math>\Upsilon_\odot</math> = 5133 [[kilogram|kg]]/[[Watt|W]] equal to a [[solar mass]] ({{Solar mass|link=y}}) divided by a [[solar luminosity]] ({{Solar luminosity|link=y}}), ({{Solar mass}}/{{Solar luminosity}}). The mass to light ratios of galaxies and clusters are all much greater than <math>\Upsilon_\odot</math> due in part to the fact that most of the [[matter]] in these objects does not reside within stars and observations suggest that a large fraction is present in the form of [[dark matter]].
Luminosities are obtained from [[photometry (astronomy)|photometric]] observations, correcting the observed [[brightness]] of the object for the [[cosmic distance ladder|distance dimming]] and [[interstellar extinction|extinction]] effects. In general, unless a complete [[electromagnetic spectrum|spectrum]] of the [[Electromagnetic radiation|radiation]] emitted by the object is obtained, a model must be extrapolated through either [[power law]] or [[blackbody]] fits. The luminosity thus obtained is known as the [[bolometric luminosity]].
Masses are often calculated from the dynamics of the [[virial theorem|virialized system]] or from [[gravitational lens]]ing. Typical mass to light ratios for galaxies range from 2 to 10 <math>\Upsilon_\odot</math> while on the largest scales, the mass to light ratio of the [[observable universe]] is approximately 100 <math>\Upsilon_\odot</math>, in concordance with the [[Lambda-CDM model|current best fit cosmological model]].
