* [[Thomas Edison]] (1847 – 1931), an American engineer and inventor.{{sfn|Сенкевич|2012|p=320}}
* [[Robert Ellwood]] (born in 1933), an American religious studies scholar, expert on world religions.{{sfn|Uchicago}} 
* [[Camille Flammarion]] (1842 – 1925), a French astronomer and writer.{{sfn|Сенкевич|2012|pp=391, 401}}
* Émile Marcault (1878 – 1968), a French psychologist and philologist.{{sfn|Theowiki1}}
* [[Charles Johnston (Theosophist)|Charles Johnston]] (1867 – 1931), an Irish Sanskrit scholar and orientalist.{{sfn|Zirkoff|1962}}
* [[I. K. Taimni|Iqbal Taimni]] (1898 – 1978), an Indian chemist and philosopher.{{sfn|Harris, Swarup}}{{sfn|Goodrick-Clarke|2008|p=239}}{{refn|group=note|Professor Rozin wrote that "some geniuses of esotericism are known not only as esotericists, but also as scientists."{{sfn|Розин|2011|p=124}}}}
* Edi Bilimoria (born in ...), an Indian [[Doctor of Philosophy|scientist]] and engineer ([[FIMechE]], [[CEng]], [[EurIng]]).{{sfn|Theowiki}}{{sfn|Goodrick-Clarke|2008|p=239}}{{refn|group=note|"The Indian-born scientist and engineer Edi D. Bilimoria has been one of the more important figures in the Theosophical discourse on science of the last decade."{{sfn|Asprem|2013|p=424}}}}
* Julia Shabanova (born in ...), an Ukrainian philosopher and [[pedagogist]].{{sfn|Шабанова|2016|p=197}}

